431
00:32:51,706 --> 00:32:57,671
And, you know, one thing that's the key takeaway for me, too, is like, I like to say in the,

432
00:32:57,851 --> 00:33:01,795
you know, we work on sound for movies is there's always like a pencils down time.

433
00:33:01,955 --> 00:33:05,758
OK, you know, we make creative decisions and then there's, you know, time where it's like

434
00:33:05,878 --> 00:33:06,819
pencils down on the test.

435
00:33:07,619 --> 00:33:12,384
Well, for this kind of thing, everybody can't have the same deadline.

436
00:33:12,704 --> 00:33:18,010
You can't have the visuals, the physical, the audio all have the same deadline because

437
00:33:18,070 --> 00:33:21,913
suddenly it's like, oh, we're tweaking things and then something else happens.

438
00:33:23,062 --> 00:33:25,165
And now our sound doesn't match the visual.

439
00:33:25,265 --> 00:33:29,009
So try to please build in time for your audio team

440
00:33:29,170 --> 00:33:31,492
to kind of be the last one standing and tweak things

441
00:33:31,552 --> 00:33:33,455
and make sure that it's right for the user.

442
00:33:34,116 --> 00:33:36,038
And then one also thing that they were able to do

443
00:33:36,118 --> 00:33:37,239
at the Austin build out,

444
00:33:38,517 --> 00:33:49,743
is to really sort of set up a way to go into the experience very graciously and then come out where you're really setting up the people to have this experience.

445
00:33:50,043 --> 00:33:53,345
So you walk into this, you know, sort of mock recruiting office and you're hearing a loop.

446
00:33:53,966 --> 00:33:59,889
of people working and typing on typewriters, and you're hearing a Victrola, and you're hearing Dan talk a little bit in the corner.

447
00:33:59,949 --> 00:34:04,112
So you're setting that mood to get people into this really intense experience.

448
00:34:04,132 --> 00:34:08,855
And then it's important to have audio as you come out of it, too, to sort of get people back into the real world.

449
00:34:08,895 --> 00:34:09,696
You don't want to just, like...

450
00:34:10,176 --> 00:34:14,979
Throws the headphones on have the six intense experience and then just sort of like kick him out the door

451
00:34:15,139 --> 00:34:16,700
Yeah, those thresholds are so important

452
00:34:16,920 --> 00:34:24,285
we think a lot about what the onboarding experiences and what the off-boarding experiences and and how you take people and these layers deeper and

453
00:34:24,325 --> 00:34:26,466
deeper into the story and into the experience

454
00:34:27,467 --> 00:34:46,995
And then, you know, I think from our point of view, one of the things that we found was a really important takeaway was this idea of working in layers and in stages and starting as flexible as you can and using that to test it, to constantly test, send people through it, be considerate of the actual end user who's going through it and what their experience is.

455
00:34:47,815 --> 00:34:53,557
And then throughput considerations. How can you find ways to build in the chance to get more people into it?

456
00:34:54,798 --> 00:35:01,023
So go to warremains.com to check out more. It's currently installed in Austin.

457
00:35:01,283 --> 00:35:04,146
And hopefully there will be some more announcements soon.

458
00:35:05,627 --> 00:35:06,248
Ethan shrugs.

459
00:35:07,128 --> 00:35:09,811
So we've got, I think, five minutes left for some questions.

460
00:35:09,851 --> 00:35:13,694
And then we'll be over at the wrap table if you want to follow up with this afterwards.

461
00:35:15,083 --> 00:35:20,268
Yeah, I have a question. I think what you've done is absolutely brilliant and utterly terrifying, even in 2D.

462
00:35:21,549 --> 00:35:26,974
I think it's a tremendous anti-war tool, you know, I mean, and I really envision it being used that way.

463
00:35:27,414 --> 00:35:32,439
But I'm wondering, with all the Civil War addicts, people who travel to Civil War battlefields,

464
00:35:32,779 --> 00:35:34,921
if you've thought of doing Gettysburg or anything like that.

465
00:35:35,316 --> 00:35:37,237
Yeah, we thought about a lot of different things.

466
00:35:37,317 --> 00:35:41,000
And so one of the things from Dan's point of view that was important at the

467
00:35:41,020 --> 00:35:44,502
beginning is that it's neither pro-war nor anti-war.

468
00:35:44,562 --> 00:35:46,423
We weren't trying to make a statement.

469
00:35:46,463 --> 00:35:53,508
We were trying to just show people the experience and the craziness of it.

470
00:35:53,528 --> 00:35:55,729
And then you're invited to draw your own conclusions.

471
00:35:55,769 --> 00:35:57,811
I think a lot of people will draw that conclusion.

472
00:35:58,731 --> 00:36:02,033
But yeah, there are a lot of different places that we could take this.

473
00:36:02,113 --> 00:36:05,835
I think it shows the power of VR as an educational tool.

474
00:36:05,915 --> 00:36:07,215
It's a way to step into history.

475
00:36:07,535 --> 00:36:08,756
Right. Thank you.

476
00:36:08,776 --> 00:36:23,022
Hi. So, my question is, did you have situations where people were freaking out because of how intense the experience is?

477
00:36:23,042 --> 00:36:23,463
Absolutely.

478
00:36:23,523 --> 00:36:27,785
And how were you trying to mitigate it in the design, or were you even trying to mitigate it?

479
00:36:28,196 --> 00:36:32,557
Well, there's one thing that I've neglected to mention as far as the setup.

480
00:36:32,697 --> 00:36:37,039
The way that we were able to set up the audio for this is it was separate.

481
00:36:37,479 --> 00:36:39,999
You know, while it was synced with the visuals, it was a separate feed.

482
00:36:40,420 --> 00:36:44,421
So if somebody, like, crouched down and cowered in the corner because they were so freaked out,

483
00:36:44,461 --> 00:36:46,901
the audio would not drop out. The audio would continue.

484
00:36:47,322 --> 00:36:52,307
And there's actually a way for an operator who's watching to tap into that audio feed

485
00:36:52,327 --> 00:36:54,930
with a microphone and make sure somebody's okay.

486
00:36:55,310 --> 00:36:58,693
So that was a really important experience to make sure, because everybody's going to

487
00:36:58,713 --> 00:37:00,115
experience this in different ways.

488
00:37:01,679 --> 00:37:06,404
Yeah, absolutely. And I mean, it, you can always take the headset off and walk away.

489
00:37:06,484 --> 00:37:15,312
Right. So that's, that's one of the important things about, about making sure that there's a way if somebody needs to go backwards through the physical space to get out, we had paths set up for that.

490
00:37:15,933 --> 00:37:25,642
And is that a part of the introduction as well? When you bring people into the experience like this, like you can do this, it's okay. Is that actually a part of the procedure?

491
00:37:26,912 --> 00:37:42,184
It was Ethan's nodding yes. I don't remember setting that up. But But yeah, I mean, it we we definitely wanted to be cognizant of people. We didn't want this to be a trigger for PTSD or anything like that. So we definitely wanted people to be able to get out of it.

492
00:37:47,408 --> 00:37:47,668
Hey, there.

