00:37:48,999 --> 00:37:51,880
I got to experience this at Tribeca.

494
00:37:51,900 --> 00:37:52,200
Sweet.

495
00:37:52,521 --> 00:37:54,421
And it was extraordinary.

496
00:37:54,881 --> 00:38:00,503
And interestingly, I had an opportunity to recount the experience to someone just a couple days ago.

497
00:38:01,564 --> 00:38:05,465
And I said, wow, it was interesting. I'm in the trenches. I feel the fans blowing.

498
00:38:05,645 --> 00:38:11,327
And I was trying to explain how from the outside, it just doesn't look like, well, it looks like a pile of stuff.

499
00:38:11,387 --> 00:38:13,288
But when you're inside, this is transformed.

500
00:38:13,688 --> 00:38:17,289
Seeing the rosary in front of you and being able to touch it, being trapped in this room.

501
00:38:18,184 --> 00:38:22,767
But at the same time, I find myself pushing the boundaries of the system, looking up over...

502
00:38:22,987 --> 00:38:28,730
There's a certain kind of fascination rather than horror, but I find myself appreciating

503
00:38:28,750 --> 00:38:32,572
getting a little closer is better than none at all.

504
00:38:33,092 --> 00:38:38,855
And the person I was talking to, who hasn't seen the experience, he countered that a little

505
00:38:38,875 --> 00:38:39,015
bit.

506
00:38:39,055 --> 00:38:43,918
He said, you know, I was reading about a Holocaust museum where they used to try to simulate

507
00:38:43,958 --> 00:38:46,239
the experience of being put in a train car.

508
00:38:46,660 --> 00:38:50,102
by herding all the guests into the elevator together and making them do that.

509
00:38:51,683 --> 00:38:57,887
And they received pushback from survivors who said, you know, you can't really recreate it.

510
00:38:58,607 --> 00:39:03,550
And they had some some qualms about going halfway without going all the way.

511
00:39:04,050 --> 00:39:08,172
So we can't totally step into history. And I'm just curious, what's the,

512
00:39:08,933 --> 00:39:11,935
is it good to get closer? Or does it help us?

513
00:39:13,777 --> 00:39:18,539
Because we can't get all the way there, it's sort of sanitizing what can't really be understood fully.

514
00:39:19,639 --> 00:39:24,141
And I mean it more as a discussion, I hope I'm not sounding critical, because it was an amazing experience,

515
00:39:24,981 --> 00:39:29,123
and yet looking at photographs of World War I is horrifying.

516
00:39:29,863 --> 00:39:32,584
We're in this kind of middle space, and I'm just curious as to your impressions.

517
00:39:32,764 --> 00:39:37,366
Yeah, totally, and I think that's a lot of where Dan was coming from in wanting to set this up,

518
00:39:37,426 --> 00:39:39,127
and his desire was very much...

519
00:39:39,987 --> 00:39:41,348
We can't get you all the way there, right?

520
00:39:41,388 --> 00:39:43,810
We don't have a time machine and we're never going to have one.

521
00:39:44,331 --> 00:39:46,652
But can we get one step closer?

522
00:39:46,732 --> 00:39:50,835
Can we get one, one degree closer to giving you the sense of what it might

523
00:39:50,875 --> 00:39:52,156
have been like to be there?

524
00:39:52,176 --> 00:39:53,617
And that, and that was the goal of this.

525
00:39:53,697 --> 00:39:58,061
And, and I do think that it was closer than, than some of the other

526
00:39:58,101 --> 00:39:59,402
ways that we can study about it.

527
00:39:59,778 --> 00:40:06,203
Well, in a lot of ways, too, it just like starts the conversation for people to go through this experience and then go from there.

528
00:40:06,343 --> 00:40:16,190
You know, maybe they it inspires them to learn more about World War One and do research or or, you know, just start talking about, you know, why did this war even happen?

529
00:40:16,670 --> 00:40:19,312
So I think it's a good thing, even though we can't get all the way there.

